Use Kafka partitions as the fan-out mechanism. The key is that Kafka distributes partitions across consumer group members, so each pod picks up one transcoding job.

```java
// Producer: publish one TranscodeJob per resolution
@Service
public class VideoUploadService {
    public void onVideoUploaded(String videoId, String s3Key) {
        List<String> resolutions = List.of("1080p", "720p", "480p", "360p", "144p");
        for (String res : resolutions) {
            // Key = videoId ensures all resolutions for one video can be correlated
            // But we fan-OUT by not using a key, allowing round-robin partition assignment
            kafkaTemplate.send("video.transcode.jobs",
                new TranscodeJob(videoId, s3Key, res));
        }
        log.info("Fanned out 5 transcode jobs for videoId={}", videoId);
    }
}
```

```java
// Consumer: each worker pod picks up jobs from its assigned partitions
@KafkaListener(topics = "video.transcode.jobs", groupId = "transcode-workers")
public void processTranscodeJob(TranscodeJob job) {
    log.info("Transcoding videoId={} to resolution={} on pod={}",
        job.videoId(), job.resolution(), podId);
    ffmpegService.transcode(job.s3Key(), job.resolution());
    s3Client.upload(outputPath, "videos/" + job.videoId() + "/" + job.resolution() + ".mp4");
    // Fan-in: publish completion event
    kafkaTemplate.send("video.transcode.complete", new TranscodeComplete(job.videoId(), job.resolution()));
}
```

```java
// Fan-in aggregator: collect all 5 completion events, then mark video as ready
@KafkaListener(topics = "video.transcode.complete", groupId = "video-status-updater")
public void onTranscodeComplete(TranscodeComplete event) {
    int completedCount = redisTemplate.opsForValue()
        .increment("transcode:" + event.videoId() + ":completed");
    if (completedCount == 5) {
        videoRepository.markReady(event.videoId());
        redisTemplate.delete("transcode:" + event.videoId() + ":completed");
        log.info("All resolutions done. videoId={} is now available.", event.videoId());
    }
}
```

```
Kafka topic: video.transcode.jobs (10 partitions, 5 consumer pods)
Pod-1 → partition 0,1 → processes 1080p + 720p jobs
Pod-2 → partition 2,3 → processes 480p + 360p jobs
Pod-3 → partition 4   → processes 144p jobs
...
Fan-in: Redis counter reaches 5 → video marked READY
```

This pattern scales horizontally: adding pods automatically rebalances Kafka partitions, distributing more jobs in parallel without any code change.

